<font color="#FF0000">ABOUT ATTITUDES</font><br>
<tt>Fri Apr 18 14:56:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have a different experience with the coverage of Kim Phuc's appearance at the Wall. Granted it was national coverage, not local, but I remember my ten year old daughter and I watching and taping everything that was portrayed on T.V. regarding her and her experiences. After the story lost its newsworthy appeal, my daughter and I discussed my memories of that event so many years ago.  As I, my daughter was impressed with all that she had endured. If nothing else, she learned that there is never a &quot;clean&quot; war as the government wanted us to believe during the Persian Gulf War, that there are always casualties, especially among civilians. My daughter has &quot;made&quot; her a hero of hers as well as with Aung San Suu Kyi of Burma and others. But most important, she understand that she was a innocent victim of war.<br><br>
Here in Hawaii, we have a fairly large Vietnamese community, and on the Island of Maui, there is a smaller community. I would assume to say that there is a wide gamut of attitudes amongst people of other races and groups. There are many vets and non-vets who can separate the war itself from the people and there are some who cannot. During the exodus of Vietnam by the boat people, it was disheartening to see the ambivalence of our government to help in their cause. But, again, there were incidents of support for this group of Vietnamese by other governments, private/public agencies and by individuals, vets and non-vets who sponsored entire families of those who did make it to our shores.<br><br>
You ask for some very hard generalities. As with any group of peoples, there are as variety of feelings and attitudes ranging from open contempt and hostility to total acceptance and respect. As my daughter is adopted and foreign born, I have taught her that there are those negatives &quot;out there&quot; but to generalize and label a group with instititutional and general racism instead of dealing with these incidences and individuals on a one by one basis would be counter productive and very tiring. I have no doubts that she will have to deal with racism and bigotry her entire life. I am a pessimist.<br><br>
For many of us vets, the war was a bad memory or a set of memories. The very structure of war ensures this to be so and there is no getting around it. Ask those of your family that survive the many years of war in their home country. As to what the Vietnamese are to those who were in combat, I think you will have to ask us on a one by one basis. I would think that you will get a set of different answers. You can e-mail me if you desire.
